Key Insights & Analysis

  • Health Impact: Average of 0.3 estimated respiratory cases per day
  • Pollution Levels: PM2.5 average of 18.9 µg/m³ (exceeds WHO guidelines)
  • Primary Correlate: PM2.5 (ug/m3) shows strongest correlation (r = 0.038)
  • Data Quality: 100.0% complete

Key Characteristics

  • "Scotland of the East" with severe economic challenges. Hill station health paradox (clean air but health burdens)
  • Tourism economy but 80% agriculture-dependent. Highest literacy, lowest income among all cities analyzed
  • Good infrastructure (NEIGRIHMS, Civil Hospital, Nazareth). But limited specialty care so patients travel outside state
  • Shillong demonstrates how high education doesn't guarantee economic development or health outcomes
    •

    *Synthetic Data Considerations

    • Population: ~517,000-520,000 (metro 2025), ~207,000 (city); literacy 92.81%; sex ratio 1042/1000; predominantly tribal population
    • Respiratory Disease: High TB burden (24/1000 in slums), respiratory morbidity peaks winter (75.5 vs 53.11 per 1000 in summer); URTI most common condition; strong PM2.5 correlation (r=0.94)
    • Healthcare: Major facilities include NEIGRIHMS (500 beds), Civil Hospital (600 beds), Nazareth Hospital (375 beds); but limited super-specialty care forces patients to seek treatment outside state
    • Seasonal Patterns: Respiratory illness surge in winter and rainy season; strong correlation with PM2.5 levels and seasonal weather changes
    • Socioeconomic: Per capita income ₹56,471 (2020-21); 80% population agriculture-dependent; GSDP ₹23,29,655 lakhs; "Scotland of the East" with tourism economy
